definitions.definition: To toil, to work.
To belabour, to emphasise or expand upon (a point in a debate, etc).
definitions.example: I think we've all got the idea. There's no need to labour the point.

definitions.definition: To be oppressed with difficulties or disease; to do one's work under conditions which make it especially hard or wearisome; to move slowly, as against opposition, or under a burden.
To suffer the pangs of childbirth.
To pitch or roll heavily, as a ship in a turbulent sea.
Expressive of strenuous effort.
definitions.example: At the end of the marathon, her laboured breathing told us she was exhausted.

definitions.definition: Of writing or speech or similar, stilted or not natural due to too much effort being used in the production.
One who nets (in any sense), or who uses a net.
An Internet user.
To specify each member of a sequence individually in incrementing order.
To determine the amount of.
To deprive of the ability to procreate.
To make unable to produce; to make unprofitable.
To kill, deactivate (denature), or destroy (break apart) all living, viable microorganisms and spores on a surface, in a fluid, or contained in a compound, such as culture media or a medical product.
To redact (a document), removing classified or sensitive material.
The quality of being unreliable.
One who practices or defends interventionism.
Of or pertaining to interventionism, or an advocate thereof.
Any of various bacteria, of the genus Rhizobium, that form nodules on the roots of legumes and fix nitrogen.
A server used to share files with other computers.
A person who makes or sells cloth or clothing.
A bot that sends mass junk e-mail.
To erase or strike out.
To eliminate completely; annihilate.
To delete permanently (e-mail etc.) that was previously marked for deletion but still stored.
That which is ceded. Insurance: (part of) a risk which is transferred from one actor to another.
The giving up of rights, property etc. which one is entitled to.
The action of impoverishing someone.
The state of being impoverished.
(followed by to or unto) To compare; to state that (something) is like (something else).
definitions.example: The physics teacher likened the effect of mass on space to an indentation in a sheet of rubber.

definitions.definition: A penalty for or consequence of a misdemeanor.
A thing forfeited; that which is taken from somebody in requital of a misdeed committed; that which is lost, or the right to which is alienated, by a crime, breach of contract, etc.
definitions.example: He who murders pays the forfeit of his own life.

definitions.definition: Something deposited and redeemable by a sportive fine as part of a game.
Injury; wrong; mischief.
A game in which forfeits are demanded.
To suffer the loss of something by wrongdoing or non-compliance
definitions.example: He forfeited his last chance of an early release from jail by repeatedly attacking another inmate.

definitions.definition: To lose a contest, game, match, or other form of competition by voluntary withdrawal, by failing to attend or participate, or by violation of the rules
definitions.example: Because only nine players were present, the football team was forced to forfeit the game.

definitions.definition: To be guilty of a misdeed; to be criminal; to transgress.
To fail to keep an obligation.
